tock Exchange]] and [[New York Stock Exchange]] as '''ACB'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4364344/justin-trudeau-marijuana-weed-legal/|title=Justin Trudeau Makes a Surprising Case For Legalizing Marijuana|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> As of late September 2018, Aurora Cannabis had eight licensed production facilities, five sales licences, and operations in 25 countries.<ref name=\"financials tmx\" /> It had a funded capacity of over 625,000 kilograms of cannabis production per annum with the bulk of capacity based in Canada and a growing presence in international markets, particularly [[Denmark]] and [[Latin America]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cbdlin.com/aurora-cannabis|title=Aurora Cannabis Inc. {{!}}|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> Aurora is the second largest cannabis company in the world by market capitalization, after [[Canopy Growth Corporation]].<ref name=\"williams\">{{cite web |author1=Sean Williams |title=Meet Marijuana's 14 Billion-Dollar Pot Stocks |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/04/29/meet-marijuanas-14-billion-dollar-pot-stocks.aspx |publisher=Motley Fool |accessdate=27 November 2019 |date=29 April 2019}}</ref> The company began trading on the [[New York Stock Exchange|NYSE]] on October 23rd, 2018 using the ticker ACB.<ref name=\"forbes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2018/09/26/whats-ahead-for-aurora-cannabis-after-an-impressive-fy-2018/#60f6a29917e5|title=What's Ahead For Aurora Cannabis After An Impressive FY 2018|publisher=Forbes|date=26 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aurora Cannabis Inc.|url=https://web.tmxmoney.com/company.php?qm_symbol=ACB|website=TSX Inc.|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref> The company is a scam.\n\nAfter significant expansion in 2018, the company reduced expenses in the second half of 2019 when the Canadian recreational cannabis market had low sales due to excessive inventory and uncompetitive pricing with the [[black market]].<ref name=\"star\">{{cite news |title=Aurora stock still sliding as it reveals executive Battley was asked to leave |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2019/12/24/aurora-stock-still-sliding-as-it-reveals-executive-battley-was-asked-to-leave.html |accessdate=26 December 2019 |work=The Toronto Star |agency=The Canadian Press |date=24 December 2019}}</ref> In February 2020, cofounder and chief executive, Terry Booth, resigned, being replaced by Executive Chairman Michael Singer as interim CEO.<ref name=\"g-cosh\">{{cite web |author1=David George-Cosh |title=Aurora Cannabis replaces CEO, sees up to $1B in write-downs |url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/aurora-cannabis-ceo-to-step-down-chairman-to-take-interim-role-1.1386220 |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=6 February 2020 |date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAurora was founded in 2006 by Terry Booth, Steve Dobler, Dale Lesack and Chris Mayerson. Booth and Dobler collectively invested over $5 million of their own capital. The founding group secured a 160+ acre parcel of land in Mountain View County, Alberta, where they established Aurora's first facility. The company received its license to grow cannabis in 2014, making it the first cannabis producer to obtain a federal license in that province.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/this-small-alberta-village-could-soon-be-home-to-the-world-s-largest-marijuana-factory-1.3865819|title=This small Alberta village could soon be home to the world's largest marijuana factory  {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref> They decided to establish the company in Alberta due to comparatively low corporate tax rates and an ideal farm credit program.<ref name=\"albertaventure.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://albertaventure.com/2016/04/marijuana-legalization-fracturing-alberta-marijuana-industry|title=Why impending legalization is fracturing the marijuana industryAlberta Venture|website=albertaventure.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615124555/https://albertaventure.com/2016/04/marijuana-legalization-fracturing-alberta-marijuana-industry/|archive-date=2018-06-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> On November 27, 2014, [[Health Canada]] issued Aurora's first license to sell medical cannabis. Since then they have built, and are operating, numerous growing facilities throughout Canada, Europe, Asia, Latin America and Oceania.<ref name=\"albertaventure.com\"/> On January 10, 2017, Aurora received a license from [[Health Canada]] to sell cannabis oils, having been granted a license to produce the oils in February 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cantechletter.com/2017/01/aurora-cannabiss-license-sell-oils-important-milestone-says-canaccord-genuity/|title=Aurora Cannabis's license to sell oils is an important milestone, says Canaccord Genuity|date=2017-01-25|work=Cantech Letter|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref> Sales of four product lines of cannabis oils commenced in April, 2017.\n\n===After legalization in Canada - October 2018===\nCanada legalized the retail sale of cannabis nationally on October 17, 2018.<ref name=\"sapra\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|last=Sapra|first=Bani|date=20 June 2018|work=[[CNN]]|access-date=}}</ref> Due to its significant capital investments, particularly in large growing facilities, Aurora had about 20% of the Canadian retail market for cannabis during early 2019.<ref name=\"fortune\">{{cite web |author1=Kevin Kelleher |title=Aurora Cannabis Earnings Reveal More Money, More Problems for Recreational Pot Sales |url=https://fortune.com/2019/02/11/aurora-cannabis-revenue-profit-canada-legalization-pot/ |publisher=Fortune |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt its year-end in June 2019, Aurora had a market capitalization of US$4.8 billion.<ref name=\"financials tmx\" /> An October 2019 report stated that cannabis stocks had \"crumbled to their lowest level since 2017\"; Aurora shares were also at a two year low.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/cannabis-business/cannabis-investing/cannabis-stocks-crumble-to-2017-lows-after-hexo-latest-to-lower-earnings-expectations |title=Cannabis stocks crumble to 2017 lows after Hexo becomes latest to lower earnings expectations |date=10 October 2019 |publisher=Financial Post |access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=Tilray fell as much 12 per cent, heading for a record low. Canopy slid 9.7 per cent, Aurora lost 5.9 per cent and Cronos Group Inc. fell 6.7 per cent.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/national-business/aurora-shares-sink-on-weak-results-and-halting-construction-of-cannabis-plants-1850091 |title=Aurora shares sink on weak results and halting construction of cannabis plants |date=15 November 2019 |publisher=Guelph Today, Canadian Press |access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=}}</ref> The fall in stock price for Aurora and other Canadian cannabis stocks in late 2019 was attributed to the missed benchmark revenues, general lack of profitability in the industry, slow rollout of retail stores in Canada, rise in [[vaping]]-related illnesses, non-competitiveness of pricing with [[black market]] cannabis, oversupply of commercial cannabis, termination of capital expenditures, and an [[FDA warning letter|FDA warning]] that [[cannabidiol]] may cause [[liver injury]], among others.<ref name=\"do\">{{cite web |author1=Kevin LaCroix |title=A Rash of Cannabis-Related Securities Class Action Lawsuits |url=https://www.dandodiary.com/2019/11/articles/securities-litigation/a-rash-of-cannabis-related-securities-class-action-lawsuits/ |publisher=The D&O Diary |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=25 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ctl\">{{cite web |author1=Jason MacLean |title=Aurora Cannabis is starting to look attractive, this investor says |url=https://www.cantechletter.com/2019/10/aurora-cannabis-is-starting-to-look-attractive-this-investor-says/ |publisher=CannTech Letter |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ctv\">{{cite news |author1=Ross Marowits |title=Aurora halts construction of two cannabis facilities to conserve cash |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/aurora-halts-construction-of-two-cannabis-facilities-to-conserve-cash-1.4687169 |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=CTV News |publisher=The Canadian Press |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"mw\">{{cite web |author1=Ciara Linnane |title=Cannabis stocks rocked as FDA warning undermines case for CBD investments |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/cannabis-stocks-rocked-as-fda-warning-undermines-case-for-cbd-investments-2019-11-26?mod=mw_quote_news |publisher=MarketWatch |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Public trading and acquisitions===\nAurora became a publicly traded company on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] on July 24, 2017,<ref name=\"cision\">{{cite web |title=Aurora Cannabis Starts Trading on Toronto Stock Exchange |url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/aurora-cannabis-starts-trading-on-toronto-stock-exchange-635823983.html |publisher=Cision |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=21 July 2017}}</ref> and on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] on October 23, 2018.<ref name=\"street\">{{cite web |author1=Tony Owusu |title=Pot Company Aurora Cannabis Sinks in Its NYSE Debut |url=https://www.thestreet.com/investing/aurora-cannabis-canada-latest-pot-company-debuts-on-nyse-tuesday-14754095 |publisher=The Street |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAurora grew through several acquisitions. By 2018, Aurora's subsidiaries included Pedanios GmbH ([[Germany]]'s largest distributor of cannabis to [[Pharmacy|pharmacies]]),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/business/local-business/aurora-cannabis-ships-medical-marijuana-to-germany-to-offset-european-supply-shortage|title=Aurora Cannabis ships medical marijuana to Germany to offset European supply shortage|date=2017-09-19|work=Edmonton Journal|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en-US}}</ref> CanvasRx (the largest medical cannabis patient outreach service in Canada),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianinsider.com/aurora-cannabis-closes-23-million-financing-and-signs-definitive-agreement-to-acquire-canvasrx|title=Aurora Cannabis Closes $23 Million Financing and Signs Definitive Agreement to Acquire CanvasRx|website=www.canadianinsider.com|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> BC Northern Lights (an indoor growing supplies manufacturer),<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/Aurora-Cannabis-Acquires-BC-Northern-Lights-and-Urban-Cultivator-564042|title=Aurora Cannabis Acquires BC Northern Lights and Urban Cultivator|last=GmbH|first=finanzen.net|work=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> Aurora-Larssen Projects (a globally leading [[greenhouse]] engineering and design consultancy),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/aurora-cannabis-to-buy-greenhouse-design-firm-larssen-terms-not-disclosed-1.3690626|title=Aurora Cannabis to buy greenhouse design firm Larssen, terms not disclosed|date=2017-11-23|work=CTVNews|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en-CA}}</ref> and H2 Biopharma (a late-stage ACMPR applicant in [[Quebec]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/Aurora-Cannabis-Completes-Larssen-and-H2-Biopharma-Acquisitions-1010347497|title=Aurora Cannabis Completes Larssen and H2 Biopharma Acquisitions|website=Markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2018, the company had a market value of C$4.5 billion; revenue in 2017 totaled C$31.1 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/getting-too-high-canadian-marijuana-stocks-skyrocket-raising-bubble-fears-2018-04-02|title=Getting too high? Canadian marijuana stocks skyrocket, raising bubble fears|first=Mike|last=Murphy|website=Marketwatch.com|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> At the time, the company was concluding its takeover merger of previous competitor [[CanniMed]] Therapeutics. The takeover was finalized in January 2018, based on a C$1.1 billion deal. The subsequent plan to purchase MedReleaf was expected to make the company the largest in Canada with a market capitalization of approximately $7 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/business/aurora-cannabis-to-buy-medreleaf-in-all-stock-deal-worth-3-2-billion-1.3928223|title=Aurora Cannabis to buy MedReleaf in all-stock deal worth $3.2 billion|first=Armina|last=Ligaya|date=14 May 2018|website=Ctvnews.ca|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"cbc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/aurora-medreleaf-pot-deal-1.4661629|title=Aurora buys MedReleaf to cement status as world's biggest cannabis company|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> Competitor [[Canopy Growth Corporation]]'s market value exceeded that amount by $3.7 billion, however after a partial takeover by [[Constellation Brands]] was announced in late August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/with-5-billion-constellation-deal-canopy-growth-is-emerging-as-the-google-of-pot|title=With $5-billion Constellation deal, Canopy Growth is emerging as the Google of pot|website=Financial Post|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>  By 24 September 2018, however, [[Tilray|Tilray Inc]]., a portfolio company of Seattle-based [[Privateer Holdings]], with growing facilities in [[Nanaimo, BC]], had become the world's second most valuable cannabis company with a market capitalization of about US$10 billion.\n\nA report in mid-September 2018 by BNN Bloomberg, stated that [[Coca-Cola]] was considering the development of cannabis-infused beverages for medical purposes (with a non-psychoactive ingredient, CBD) and was in preliminary discussion with Aurora. Although Coke and Aurora then announced that they were merely studying the market, and had no plan to announce regarding the distribution of such products.<ref>{{cite web|author=Christina Pellegrini|title=Aurora says there isn\u2019t a deal with Coca-Cola on marijuana-based drinks|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/cannabis/article-aurora-responds-to-report-of-talks-with-coca-cola/|website=Globe and Mail|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref> Aurora's shares increased and its market cap reached US$10.71 billion on September 18, 2018.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/quote/ACB:CN CB:CNToronto Aurora Cannabis Inc]</ref> On 20 September 2018, [[Tilray Inc]]., a portfolio company of Seattle-based [[Privateer Holdings]], with growing facilities in Nanaimo, BC, had become the world's most valuable cannabis company, but a major drop in share price (and a subsequent market capitalization of about US$10 billion) made it only the third largest, after Canopy Growth and Aurora.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/24/tilray-shares-wipe-out-gains-from-last-weeks-wild-ride.html |title=Pot stock Tilray tumbles, completely wiping out gains from last week's wild surge|publisher=CNBC|date=September 24, 2018 |accessdate=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Class action lawsuits in the United States===\nDuring the fourth quarter of 2019, several [[law firm]]s in the United States announced [[class action lawsuit]]s against Aurora, citing the abrupt decline in stock price, failure to complete planned capital investments, and missed revenue and profit forecasts by the company as misleading to public investors.<ref name=do/><ref name=\"elango\">{{cite web |author1=Nivedha Elango |title=Aurora Cannabis Hit with Securities Lawsuits |url=https://420investordaily.com/2019/11/25/aurora-cannabis-hit-with-securities-lawsuits/ |publisher=420 Investor Daily |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company is a scam once the reverse stock split of 1:12 occurs on May 12th 2020\n\n===Status at end of 2019===\nDuring an interview in November 2019, CEO Terry Booth discussed the poor retail performance of the Canadian cannabis industry, saying that \"carnage\" was possible unless certain producers were able to reduce the cost of operations when oversupply existed.<ref name=cosh/> In December, two of Aurora's senior executives departed the company: Chief Global Business Development Officer, Neil Belot,<ref name=\"lamers\">{{cite web |author1=Matt Lamers |title=Executives Belot and Battley exit struggling Aurora Cannabis |url=https://mjbizdaily.com/battley-steps-down-as-aurora-cannabis-executive-joins-medreleaf-australia-board/ |publisher=Marijuana Business Daily |accessdate=26 December 2019 |date=23 December 2019}}</ref> and Chief Corporate Officer, Cam Battley,<ref name=star/> when the price of the company's stock had dropped 61% over 2019.<ref name=\"mr\">{{cite web |author1=Rajiv Nanjapla |title=Aurora Cannabis Releases Update on Cannabis 2.0 |url=https://marketrealist.com/2019/12/aurora-cannabis-releases-update-on-cannabis/ |publisher=Market Realist |accessdate=26 December 2019 |date=24 December 2019}}</ref> During the fourth quarter of 2019, the company had suspended cannabis production in Denmark and at its greenhouses in [[Medicine Hat]], Alberta.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/national-business/aurora-shares-sink-on-weak-results-and-halting-construction-of-cannabis-plants-1850091 |title=Aurora shares sink on weak results and halting construction of cannabis plants |date=15 November 2019 |publisher=Guelph Today, Canadian Press |access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref> The company's 15,000-square-foot, non-operational, greenhouse in [[Exeter, Ontario]] was also listed for sale. This was part of the goal to \"reduce its expenses and boost its cash balance after a series of weak quarters,\" according to a news report.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/cannabis-business/aurora-selling-exeter-greenhouse-in-bid-to-raise-cash-cut-expenses |title=Aurora Cannabis is selling one of its biggest greenhouses to raise cash \u2014 and analysts are applauding |date=7 January 2020 |publisher=Financial Post |access-date=8 January 2020 |quote=MKM Partners analyst says he expects $2-billion worth of writedowns}}</ref> The company's second quarter report (for the period ending 31 December 2019) indicated a loss of US $981 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/aurora-cannabis-shares-rise-after-an-earnings-report-that-was-mostly-expected-2020-02-13 |title=Aurora Cannabis shares rise after a dire earnings report and $1 billion loss|authors=Ciara Linnane and Max A. Cherney |date=14 February 2020 |publisher=Marketwatch |access-date=14 February 2020 |quote=shares rose 2% after the company posted a $981 million loss and batch of earnings that were mostly expected}}</ref>\n\nAurora claimed it had reduced the cost of producing cannabis to $0.85 per gram, when the national retail price of cannabis in Canada was $7.37 per gram.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pot price in Canada falls 6.4 per cent to $7.37 a gram: StatCan |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/pot-price-in-canada-falls-6-4-per-cent-to-7-37-a-gram-statcan-1.4630721 |accessdate=26 December 2019 |work=CTV News |agency=The Canadian Press |date=9 October 2019}}</ref> In December, Aurora announced its release of products for \"Cannabis 2.0\" &ndash; the retail market for edible cannabis products &ndash; to include [[gummy candy|gummies]], [[chocolate]]s, [[List of baked goods|baked goods]], and [[mint candy|mints]].<ref name=mr/><ref>{{cite news |title=Aurora Cannabis Announces First Quarter 2020 Results & Corporate Action Plan |url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/aurora-cannabis-announces-first-quarter-2020-results-amp-corporate-action-plan-874896491.html |accessdate=26 December 2019 |work=Cision |agency=Aurora Cannabis Inc. |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Earlier acquisitions and growth ==\nAurora owns Pedanios GmbH, a wholesale importer, exporter, and distributor of medical cannabis in the European Union, based in Berlin, Germany. Pedanios is the EU's largest distributor of cannabis by volume of product sold. As of March 2018, it is one of three distributors to offer cannabis flowers sourced from both Canada and the Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/aurora-cannabis-and-its-subsidiary-pedanios-gmbh-both-receive-eu-gmp-certification-1010933798|title=Aurora Cannabis and its Subsidiary Pedanios GmbH Both Receive EU GMP Certification {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen.net|work=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2018-06-26}}</ref>\n\nIn January, 2018, Aurora became the first private company to be granted a supply agreement to the Italian market through its German subsidiary Pedanios. Aurora announced on January 23, 2018 that the first tender would consist of three lots of different cannabinoid profiles totalling 100&nbsp;kg.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/aurora-medical-cannabis-italy-1.4494494|title=Alberta medical marijuana supplier expands sales to Italy {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-06-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nA statement from the company in early October 2019 reported a funding capacity for over 625,000 kg of cannabis per year, with sales and operations in 25 countries.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/aurora-cannabis-provides-update-on-global-operations-and-growth-initiatives-891846040.html|title=Aurora Cannabis Provides Update on Global Operations and Growth Initiatives|work=Cision|agency=Aurora Cannabis Inc.|date=3 October 2019}}</ref> Weeks later however, the company was reported to be having cash flow problems and the value of its stock had dropped significantly.<ref name=star/><ref name=\"cosh\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/aurora-ceo-eyes-u-s-amid-looming-carnage-for-canadian-pot-industry-1.1355362|title=Aurora CEO eyes U.S. amid looming 'carnage' for Canadian pot industry|work=BNN Bloomberg|date=29 November 2019|author=David George-Cosh|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== CanniMed takeover ===\nOn November 13, 2017, Aurora Cannabis delivered an all-stock takeover bid to [[CanniMed|CanniMed Therapeutics]]'s board of directors, which became public on November 14.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/cannimed-therapeutics-aurora-cannnabis-takeover-bid-1.4403189|title=CanniMed tells shareholders to wait while it reviews Aurora offer|work=CBC News|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en}}</ref> It claimed that it had the support of 38% of shareholders.<ref name=\":2\" /> CanniMed management responded by rejecting the offer, and proposed an alternative merger with Newstrike Resources, a recreational cannabis firm, instead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/aurora-cannabis-cannimed-therapeutics-takeover-bid-1.4417757|title=Aurora takeover bid 'makes no sense,' based on inflated share price: CanniMed|work=CBC News|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en}}</ref>  CanniMed also enacted a \"[[Shareholder rights plan|poison pill]]\" to fend off the acquisition by enacting a rights plan that would allow CanniMed shareholders to vote on the Newstrike deal.  On November 20, Aurora launched a [[hostile takeover]] bid for CanniMed, conditional on shareholders rejecting the Newstrike deal.\n\nThe Ontario Securities Commission intervened in this, the first major hostile takeover bid in Canada's cannabis industry, ordering Aurora Cannabis Inc. to provide more disclosure regarding any ties to individuals \"in a special relationship\" with target CanniMed Therapeutics Inc. and blocking CanniMed from adopting the so-called \"poison pill\" defence.  The ties were deemed unfounded by the Securities Commission.  On January 17, 2018, Newstrike shareholders approved the proposed merger.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ca.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idCAKBN1F62YO-OCABS|title=Up Cannabis-parent Newstrike's shareholders approve sale to CanniMed|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=CA|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en-CA}}</ref>  On January 18, CanniMed postponed its shareholder vote on the Newstrike deal, submitting that it will hold talks with suitor Aurora Cannabis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/news/cannimed-postpones-shareholder-vote-will-hold-talks-with-suitor-aurora-cannabis|title=CanniMed postpones shareholder vote, will hold talks with suitor Aurora Cannabis|website=business.financialpost.com|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> On January 24, it was announced that Aurora Cannabis finally hammered out a deal to acquire CanniMed Therapeutics Inc. for $1.1 billion, and CanniMed dropped its plans to acquire Newstrike.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/commodities/agriculture/nobody-got-any-sleep-last-night-aurora-cannabis-lands-cannimed-for-1-1-billion-after-marathon-talks|title='Nobody got any sleep': Aurora Cannabis lands CanniMed after marathon talks|website=business.financialpost.com|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Aurora completed their acquisition of Cannimed, with both parties agreeing to the transaction on friendly terms. This agreement brought Aurora's total patient count to 42,000 registered cannabis patients in Canada.\n\n=== MedReleaf takeover ===\nIn mid-May 2018, the company announced a planned friendly takeover of MedReleaf in a $3.2 billion stock deal already approved by the directors of both companies. The deal still requires approval by shareholders and government regulators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/business/aurora-cannabis-to-buy-medreleaf-in-all-stock-deal-worth-3-2-billion-1.3928223|title=Aurora Cannabis to buy MedReleaf in all-stock deal worth $3.2 billion|first=Armina|last=Ligaya|date=14 May 2018|website=Ctybews.ca|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> After the takeover is completed, the company will be able to produce 570,000 kilograms of cannabis at its nine grow operations in Canada and two in [[Denmark]], if it uses all of the available capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/canopy-growths-position-as-top-global-cannabis-company-shaken-by-merger-of-two-rivals|title=Canopy Growth's position as top global cannabis company shaken by merger of two rivals|date=15 May 2018|website=Ottawacitizen.com|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> The value of the new company could be as high as $7 billion, making it substantially larger than [[Canopy Growth Corporation]] with its market cap of $6.45 billion.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/our-eyes-are-on-the-global-market-aurora-acquires-medreleaf-in-largest-cannabis-deal-yet|title='Our eyes are on the global market': Aurora acquires MedReleaf in largest cannabis deal yet|date=14 May 2018|website=Business.financialpost.com|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> It would have distribution agreements in a number of countries, including Germany, [[Italy]], [[Brazil]] and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2018/05/14/edmontons-aurora-cannabis-buys-medreleaf-for-32-billion-becoming-largest-cannabis-producer-in-the-world.html|title=Edmonton's Aurora Cannabis buys MedReleaf for $3.2-billion, becoming 'largest cannabis producer in the world'  |website=Thestar.com|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> MedReleaf's German Partner filed damage claims against Aurora and MedReleaf in October 2018 for breaching the exclusive supply 2 years supply agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leafly.com/news/industry/cannamedical-sues-aurora-failed-deliveries|date=8 Nov 2018|website=Leafly.com|title=Failed Deliveries Could Cost Canadian LPs \u20ac14.7 Million|accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref> Cannamedical had sponsored MedReleaf's Markham EU-GMP certification and played a decisive role in the successful completion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/medreleaf-receives-eu-gmp-certification-for-shipment-from-its-markham-facility-and-completes-first-export-to-cannamedical-pharma-in-germany-687868341.html|date=11 July 2018|website=Newswire.com|title= MedReleaf receives EU GMP certification for shipment from its Markham facility and completes first export to Cannamedical Pharma in Germany|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Growing facilities==\n[[File:AuroraSky.jpg|thumb|Aurora Cannabis green house and Headquarters at [[Edmonton International Airport]]]]\nAurora has three operational facilities in [[Canada]] (Aurora Sky, Aurora Vie, and Aurora Mountain) plus two new facilities projected to be operational by the end of 2019, including a 1,000,000 square foot facility under construction in [[Odense|Odense, Denmark]]. Construction on the Nordic 2 project in Denmark was stopped in November 2019 when the company's stock dropped to a two year low. The Aurora Sun project in Alberta was put on a temporary hold. These decisions would lead to a savings of $190 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/national-business/aurora-shares-sink-on-weak-results-and-halting-construction-of-cannabis-plants-1850091 |title=Aurora shares sink on weak results and halting construction of cannabis plants |date=15 November 2019 |publisher=Guelph Today, Canadian Press |access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=Aurora announced after markets closed on Thursday that it will immediately cease construction of its Aurora Nordic 2 facility in Denmark to save about $80 million over the next year, as well as indefinitely defer completion of construction and commissioning at its Aurora Sun facility in Alberta to conserve $110 million.}}</ref>  \n\nAurora Mountain was Aurora's first facility, completed in 2015. It is a 55,200-square-foot production facility in [[Mountain View County, Alberta|Mountain View County]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAurora Vie is a 40,000-square-foot, fully licensed, indoor production facility in [[Pointe-Claire]], [[Quebec]]. It was the second licensed producer in Quebec, and was acquired in 2017 for $7 million when it was about 80% complete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hortidaily.com/article/38853/CAN-(QC)-Aurora-receives-cultivation-license-for-Pointe-Claire-site|title=Aurora receives cultivation license for Pointe-Claire site|website=www.hortidaily.com|access-date=2018-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120124243/http://www.hortidaily.com/article/38853/CAN-(QC)-Aurora-receives-cultivation-license-for-Pointe-Claire-site|archive-date=2018-01-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Aurora Cannabis began construction of an automated 800,000-square-foot plant in [[Alberta]] that it said would be capable of producing 100,000 kilograms of cannabis annually.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plant.ca/features/166604/|title=Aurora Sky rolls a big one|website=www.plant.ca|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> The land is part of the acreage owned by the [[Edmonton International Airport]].\n\n== Testing ==\nAll products are third-party laboratory tested with results displayed on the company's website and mobile app. In March 2017, Aurora allowed public access to a simplified Certificate of Analysis (CoA) for every cannabis product available for sale on the company's online store and mobile app. The system was developed in partnership with Anandia Labs Inc., a Canadian cannabis genetics and testing laboratory.\n\n==Retail==\nAs of April 2019, Aurora had about 17 retail outlets in western Canada through its [[strategic partnership]] with Choom Holdings Inc. and [[Mergers and acquisitions|acquisition]] of Clarity Cannabis Retail Stores, with 52 more store locations in development.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Top 5 Cannabis Retail Brands in Canada |url=https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2019/04/01/1790669/0/en/The-Top-5-Cannabis-Retail-Brands-in-Canada.html |accessdate=27 November 2019 |work=Mugglehead Media Corp |publisher=Global News |date=1 April 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Aurora opened an 11,000 [[square foot]] (1,022 square meters) [[flagship]] retail store in [[West Edmonton Mall]], making the store the largest cannabis retail space in Canada.<ref name=\"gn\">{{cite news |author1=Phil Heidenreich |title=Aurora Cannabis opening 11,000-square-foot store at West Edmonton Mall |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6221550/aurora-cannabis-stores-west-edmonton-mall/ |work=Global News |accessdate=27 November 2019 |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://auroramj.com/ Aurora Cannabis Website]\n\n{{Edmonton Businesses}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aurora Cannabis}}\n[[Category:Medicinal use of cannabis organizations]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Cannabis companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Cannabis in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian companies established in 2006]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian cannabis company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Aurora Cannabis Inc.\n| logo = Aurora_Cannabis_logo.svg\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{TSX|ACB}}\n| ISIN = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| founders = Terry Booth, Steve Dobler, Chris Mayerson, Dale Lesack\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| fate = \n| area_served = [[Canada]], [[Europe]], [[Australia]]\n| key_people = Michael Singer (interim CEO)\n| industry = [[Cannabis industry|Cannabis]]\n| services = \n| revenue = {{increase}} [[C$]] 248 million <small>(June 2019)</small><ref name=\"financials tmx\">{{cite web|title=Aurora Cannabis Inc.|url=https://web.tmxmoney.com/financials.php?qm_symbol=ACB&type=BalanceSheet&rtype=A|website=TMX Money|publisher=QuoteMedia|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{decrease}} [[C$]] -297 million <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials tmx\" />\n| net_income = {{decrease}} [[C$]] -291 million <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials tmx\" />\n| assets = {{increase}} [[C$]] 5.5 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials tmx\" />\n| equity = {{increase}} [[C$]] 4.4 billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials tmx\" />\n| owner = \n| num_employees = 2779\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = Pedanios GmbH, Urban Cultivator, Australis Capital Inc., CanvasRx Inc., H2 Biopharma Inc., Peloton Pharmaceuticals Inc., Aurora Larssen Projects Ltd., Larssen Ltd., Aurora Cannabis Enterprises Inc., BC Northern Lights Enterprises Ltd., Medreleaf (Australia)\n| homepage = {{url|https://www.auroramj.com/}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n| caption = \n| foundation = {{Start date|2006}}\n| location_city = [[Edmonton]]\n| location_country = [[Canada]]\n| location = \n| locations = \n}}\n'''Aurora Cannabis Inc.''' is a Canadian licensed [[Cannabis in Canada|cannabis producer]], headquartered in [[Edmonton]]. It trades on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] and [[New York Stock Exchange]] as '''ACB'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4364344/justin-trudeau-marijuana-weed-legal/|title=Justin Trudeau Makes a Surprising Case For Legalizing Marijuana|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> As of late September 2018, Aurora Cannabis had eight licensed production facilities, five sales licences, and operations in 25 countries.<ref name=\"financials tmx\" /> It had a funded capacity of over 625,000 kilograms of cannabis production per annum with the bulk of capacity based in Canada and a growing presence in international markets, particularly [[Denmark]] and [[Latin America]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cbdlin.com/aurora-cannabis|title=Aurora Cannabis Inc. {{!}}|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> Aurora is the second largest cannabis company in the world by market capitalization, after [[Canopy Growth Corporation]].<ref name=\"williams\">{{cite web |author1=Sean Williams |title=Meet Marijuana's 14 Billion-Dollar Pot Stocks |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/04/29/meet-marijuanas-14-billion-dollar-pot-stocks.aspx |publisher=Motley Fool |accessdate=27 November 2019 |date=29 April 2019}}</ref> The company began trading on the [[New York Stock Exchange|NYSE]] on October 23rd, 2018 using the ticker ACB.<ref name=\"forbes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2018/09/26/whats-ahead-for-aurora-cannabis-after-an-impressive-fy-2018/#60f6a29917e5|title=What's Ahead For Aurora Cannabis After An Impressive FY 2018|publisher=Forbes|date=26 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aurora Cannabis Inc.|url=https://web.tmxmoney.com/company.php?qm_symbol=ACB|website=TSX Inc.|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter significant expansion in 2018, the company reduced expenses in the second half of 2019 when the Canadian recreational cannabis market had low sales due to excessive inventory and uncompetitive pricing with the [[black market]].<ref name=\"star\">{{cite news |title=Aurora stock still sliding as it reveals executive Battley was asked to leave |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2019/12/24/aurora-stock-still-sliding-as-it-reveals-executive-battley-was-asked-to-leave.html |accessdate=26 December 2019 |work=The Toronto Star |agency=The Canadian Press |date=24 December 2019}}</ref> In February 2020, cofounder and chief executive, Terry Booth, resigned, being replaced by Executive Chairman Michael Singer as interim CEO.<ref name=\"g-cosh\">{{cite web |author1=David George-Cosh |title=Aurora Cannabis replaces CEO, sees up to $1B in write-downs |url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/aurora-cannabis-ceo-to-step-down-chairman-to-take-interim-role-1.1386220 |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=6 February 2020 |date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAurora was founded in 2006 by Terry Booth, Steve Dobler, Dale Lesack and Chris Mayerson. Booth and Dobler collectively invested over $5 million of their own capital. The founding group secured a 160+ acre parcel of land in Mountain View County, Alberta, where they established Aurora's first facility. The company received its license to grow cannabis in 2014, making it the first cannabis producer to obtain a federal license in that province.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/this-small-alberta-village-could-soon-be-home-to-the-world-s-largest-marijuana-factory-1.3865819|title=This small Alberta village could soon be home to the world's largest marijuana factory  {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref> They decided to establish the company in Alberta due to comparatively low corporate tax rates and an ideal farm credit program.<ref name=\"albertaventure.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://albertaventure.com/2016/04/marijuana-legalization-fracturing-alberta-marijuana-industry|title=Why impending legalization is fracturing the marijuana industryAlberta Venture|website=albertaventure.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615124555/https://albertaventure.com/2016/04/marijuana-legalization-fracturing-alberta-marijuana-industry/|archive-date=2018-06-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> On November 27, 2014, [[Health Canada]] issued Aurora's first license to sell medical cannabis. Since then they have built, and are operating, numerous growing facilities throughout Canada, Europe, Asia, Latin America and Oceania.<ref name=\"albertaventure.com\"/> On January 10, 2017, Aurora received a license from [[Health Canada]] to sell cannabis oils, having been granted a license to produce the oils in February 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cantechletter.com/2017/01/aurora-cannabiss-license-sell-oils-important-milestone-says-canaccord-genuity/|title=Aurora Cannabis's license to sell oils is an important milestone, says Canaccord Genuity|date=2017-01-25|work=Cantech Letter|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US}}</ref> Sales of four product lines of cannabis oils commenced in April, 2017.\n\n===After legalization in Canada - October 2018===\nCanada legalized the retail sale of cannabis nationally on October 17, 2018.<ref name=\"sapra\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|last=Sapra|first=Bani|date=20 June 2018|work=[[CNN]]|access-date=}}</ref> Due to its significant capital investments, particularly in large growing facilities, Aurora had about 20% of the Canadian retail market for cannabis during early 2019.<ref name=\"fortune\">{{cite web |author1=Kevin Kelleher |title=Aurora Cannabis Earnings Reveal More Money, More Problems for Recreational Pot Sales |url=https://fortune.com/2019/02/11/aurora-cannabis-revenue-profit-canada-legalization-pot/ |publisher=Fortune |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt its year-end in June 2019, Aurora had a market capitalization of US$4.8 billion.<ref name=\"financials tmx\" /> An October 2019 report stated that cannabis stocks had \"crumbled to their lowest level since 2017\"; Aurora shares were also at a two year low.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/cannabis-business/cannabis-investing/cannabis-stocks-crumble-to-2017-lows-after-hexo-latest-to-lower-earnings-expectations |title=Cannabis stocks crumble to 2017 lows after Hexo becomes latest to lower earnings expectations |date=10 October 2019 |publisher=Financial Post |access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=Tilray fell as much 12 per cent, heading for a record low. Canopy slid 9.7 per cent, Aurora lost 5.9 per cent and Cronos Group Inc. fell 6.7 per cent.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/national-business/aurora-shares-sink-on-weak-results-and-halting-construction-of-cannabis-plants-1850091 |title=Aurora shares sink on weak results and halting construction of cannabis plants |date=15 November 2019 |publisher=Guelph Today, Canadian Press |access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=}}</ref> The fall in stock price for Aurora and other Canadian cannabis stocks in late 2019 was attributed to the missed benchmark revenues, general lack of profitability in the industry, slow rollout of retail stores in Canada, rise in [[vaping]]-related illnesses, non-competitiveness of pricing with [[black market]] cannabis, oversupply of commercial cannabis, termination of capital expenditures, and an [[FDA warning letter|FDA warning]] that [[cannabidiol]] may cause [[liver injury]], among others.<ref name=\"do\">{{cite web |author1=Kevin LaCroix |title=A Rash of Cannabis-Related Securities Class Action Lawsuits |url=https://www.dandodiary.com/2019/11/articles/securities-litigation/a-rash-of-cannabis-related-securities-class-action-lawsuits/ |publisher=The D&O Diary |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=25 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ctl\">{{cite web |author1=Jason MacLean |title=Aurora Cannabis is starting to look attractive, this investor says |url=https://www.cantechletter.com/2019/10/aurora-cannabis-is-starting-to-look-attractive-this-investor-says/ |publisher=CannTech Letter |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ctv\">{{cite news |author1=Ross Marowits |title=Aurora halts construction of two cannabis facilities to conserve cash |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/aurora-halts-construction-of-two-cannabis-facilities-to-conserve-cash-1.4687169 |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=CTV News |publisher=The Canadian Press |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"mw\">{{cite web |author1=Ciara Linnane |title=Cannabis stocks rocked as FDA warning undermines case for CBD investments |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/cannabis-stocks-rocked-as-fda-warning-undermines-case-for-cbd-investments-2019-11-26?mod=mw_quote_news |publisher=MarketWatch |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Public trading and acquisitions===\nAurora became a publicly traded company on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] on July 24, 2017,<ref name=\"cision\">{{cite web |title=Aurora Cannabis Starts Trading on Toronto Stock Exchange |url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/aurora-cannabis-starts-trading-on-toronto-stock-exchange-635823983.html |publisher=Cision |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=21 July 2017}}</ref> and on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] on October 23, 2018.<ref name=\"street\">{{cite web |author1=Tony Owusu |title=Pot Company Aurora Cannabis Sinks in Its NYSE Debut |url=https://www.thestreet.com/investing/aurora-cannabis-canada-latest-pot-company-debuts-on-nyse-tuesday-14754095 |publisher=The Street |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAurora grew through several acquisitions. By 2018, Aurora's subsidiaries included Pedanios GmbH ([[Germany]]'s largest distributor of cannabis to [[Pharmacy|pharmacies]]),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/business/local-business/aurora-cannabis-ships-medical-marijuana-to-germany-to-offset-european-supply-shortage|title=Aurora Cannabis ships medical marijuana to Germany to offset European supply shortage|date=2017-09-19|work=Edmonton Journal|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en-US}}</ref> CanvasRx (the largest medical cannabis patient outreach service in Canada),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianinsider.com/aurora-cannabis-closes-23-million-financing-and-signs-definitive-agreement-to-acquire-canvasrx|title=Aurora Cannabis Closes $23 Million Financing and Signs Definitive Agreement to Acquire CanvasRx|website=www.canadianinsider.com|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> BC Northern Lights (an indoor growing supplies manufacturer),<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/Aurora-Cannabis-Acquires-BC-Northern-Lights-and-Urban-Cultivator-564042|title=Aurora Cannabis Acquires BC Northern Lights and Urban Cultivator|last=GmbH|first=finanzen.net|work=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> Aurora-Larssen Projects (a globally leading [[greenhouse]] engineering and design consultancy),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/aurora-cannabis-to-buy-greenhouse-design-firm-larssen-terms-not-disclosed-1.3690626|title=Aurora Cannabis to buy greenhouse design firm Larssen, terms not disclosed|date=2017-11-23|work=CTVNews|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en-CA}}</ref> and H2 Biopharma (a late-stage ACMPR applicant in [[Quebec]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/Aurora-Cannabis-Completes-Larssen-and-H2-Biopharma-Acquisitions-1010347497|title=Aurora Cannabis Completes Larssen and H2 Biopharma Acquisitions|website=Markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2018, the company had a market value of C$4.5 billion; revenue in 2017 totaled C$31.1 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/getting-too-high-canadian-marijuana-stocks-skyrocket-raising-bubble-fears-2018-04-02|title=Getting too high? Canadian marijuana stocks skyrocket, raising bubble fears|first=Mike|last=Murphy|website=Marketwatch.com|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> At the time, the company was concluding its takeover merger of previous competitor [[CanniMed]] Therapeutics. The takeover was finalized in January 2018, based on a C$1.1 billion deal. The subsequent plan to purchase MedReleaf was expected to make the company the largest in Canada with a market capitalization of approximately $7 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/business/aurora-cannabis-to-buy-medreleaf-in-all-stock-deal-worth-3-2-billion-1.3928223|title=Aurora Cannabis to buy MedReleaf in all-stock deal worth $3.2 billion|first=Armina|last=Ligaya|date=14 May 2018|website=Ctvnews.ca|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"cbc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/aurora-medreleaf-pot-deal-1.4661629|title=Aurora buys MedReleaf to cement status as world's biggest cannabis company|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> Competitor [[Canopy Growth Corporation]]'s market value exceeded that amount by $3.7 billion, however after a partial takeover by [[Constellation Brands]] was announced in late August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/with-5-billion-constellation-deal-canopy-growth-is-emerging-as-the-google-of-pot|title=With $5-billion Constellation deal, Canopy Growth is emerging as the Google of pot|website=Financial Post|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>  By 24 September 2018, however, [[Tilray|Tilray Inc]]., a portfolio company of Seattle-based [[Privateer Holdings]], with growing facilities in [[Nanaimo, BC]], had become the world's second most valuable cannabis company with a market capitalization of about US$10 billion.\n\nA report in mid-September 2018 by BNN Bloomberg, stated that [[Coca-Cola]] was considering the development of cannabis-infused beverages for medical purposes (with a non-psychoactive ingredient, CBD) and was in preliminary discussion with Aurora. Although Coke and Aurora then announced that they were merely studying the market, and had no plan to announce regarding the distribution of such products.<ref>{{cite web|author=Christina Pellegrini|title=Aurora says there isn\u2019t a deal with Coca-Cola on marijuana-based drinks|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/cannabis/article-aurora-responds-to-report-of-talks-with-coca-cola/|website=Globe and Mail|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref> Aurora's shares increased and its market cap reached US$10.71 billion on September 18, 2018.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/quote/ACB:CN CB:CNToronto Aurora Cannabis Inc]</ref> On 20 September 2018, [[Tilray Inc]]., a portfolio company of Seattle-based [[Privateer Holdings]], with growing facilities in Nanaimo, BC, had become the world's most valuable cannabis company, but a major drop in share price (and a subsequent market capitalization of about US$10 billion) made it only the third largest, after Canopy Growth and Aurora.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/24/tilray-shares-wipe-out-gains-from-last-weeks-wild-ride.html |title=Pot stock Tilray tumbles, completely wiping out gains from last week's wild surge|publisher=CNBC|date=September 24, 2018 |accessdate=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Class action lawsuits in the United States===\nDuring the fourth quarter of 2019, several [[law firm]]s in the United States announced [[class action lawsuit]]s against Aurora, citing the abrupt decline in stock price, failure to complete planned capital investments, and missed revenue and profit forecasts by the company as misleading to public investors.<ref name=do/><ref name=\"elango\">{{cite web |author1=Nivedha Elango |title=Aurora Cannabis Hit with Securities Lawsuits |url=https://420investordaily.com/2019/11/25/aurora-cannabis-hit-with-securities-lawsuits/ |publisher=420 Investor Daily |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Status at end of 2019===\nDuring an interview in November 2019, CEO Terry Booth discussed the poor retail performance of the Canadian cannabis industry, saying that \"carnage\" was possible unless certain producers were able to reduce the cost of operations when oversupply existed.<ref name=cosh/> In December, two of Aurora's senior executives departed the company: Chief Global Business Development Officer, Neil Belot,<ref name=\"lamers\">{{cite web |author1=Matt Lamers |title=Executives Belot and Battley exit struggling Aurora Cannabis |url=https://mjbizdaily.com/battley-steps-down-as-aurora-cannabis-executive-joins-medreleaf-australia-board/ |publisher=Marijuana Business Daily |accessdate=26 December 2019 |date=23 December 2019}}</ref> and Chief Corporate Officer, Cam Battley,<ref name=star/> when the price of the company's stock had dropped 61% over 2019.<ref name=\"mr\">{{cite web |author1=Rajiv Nanjapla |title=Aurora Cannabis Releases Update on Cannabis 2.0 |url=https://marketrealist.com/2019/12/aurora-cannabis-releases-update-on-cannabis/ |publisher=Market Realist |accessdate=26 December 2019 |date=24 December 2019}}</ref> During the fourth quarter of 2019, the company had suspended cannabis production in Denmark and at its greenhouses in [[Medicine Hat]], Alberta.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/national-business/aurora-shares-sink-on-weak-results-and-halting-construction-of-cannabis-plants-1850091 |title=Aurora shares sink on weak results and halting construction of cannabis plants |date=15 November 2019 |publisher=Guelph Today, Canadian Press |access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref> The company's 15,000-square-foot, non-operational, greenhouse in [[Exeter, Ontario]] was also listed for sale. This was part of the goal to \"reduce its expenses and boost its cash balance after a series of weak quarters,\" according to a news report.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/cannabis-business/aurora-selling-exeter-greenhouse-in-bid-to-raise-cash-cut-expenses |title=Aurora Cannabis is selling one of its biggest greenhouses to raise cash \u2014 and analysts are applauding |date=7 January 2020 |publisher=Financial Post |access-date=8 January 2020 |quote=MKM Partners analyst says he expects $2-billion worth of writedowns}}</ref> The company's second quarter report (for the period ending 31 December 2019) indicated a loss of US $981 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/aurora-cannabis-shares-rise-after-an-earnings-report-that-was-mostly-expected-2020-02-13 |title=Aurora Cannabis shares rise after a dire earnings report and $1 billion loss|authors=Ciara Linnane and Max A. Cherney |date=14 February 2020 |publisher=Marketwatch |access-date=14 February 2020 |quote=shares rose 2% after the company posted a $981 million loss and batch of earnings that were mostly expected}}</ref>\n\nAurora claimed it had reduced the cost of producing cannabis to $0.85 per gram, when the national retail price of cannabis in Canada was $7.37 per gram.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pot price in Canada falls 6.4 per cent to $7.37 a gram: StatCan |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/pot-price-in-canada-falls-6-4-per-cent-to-7-37-a-gram-statcan-1.4630721 |accessdate=26 December 2019 |work=CTV News |agency=The Canadian Press |date=9 October 2019}}</ref> In December, Aurora announced its release of products for \"Cannabis 2.0\" &ndash; the retail market for edible cannabis products &ndash; to include [[gummy candy|gummies]], [[chocolate]]s, [[List of baked goods|baked goods]], and [[mint candy|mints]].<ref name=mr/><ref>{{cite news |title=Aurora Cannabis Announces First Quarter 2020 Results & Corporate Action Plan |url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/aurora-cannabis-announces-first-quarter-2020-results-amp-corporate-action-plan-874896491.html |accessdate=26 December 2019 |work=Cision |agency=Aurora Cannabis Inc. |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Earlier acquisitions and growth ==\nAurora owns Pedanios GmbH, a wholesale importer, exporter, and distributor of medical cannabis in the European Union, based in Berlin, Germany. Pedanios is the EU's largest distributor of cannabis by volume of product sold. As of March 2018, it is one of three distributors to offer cannabis flowers sourced from both Canada and the Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/aurora-cannabis-and-its-subsidiary-pedanios-gmbh-both-receive-eu-gmp-certification-1010933798|title=Aurora Cannabis and its Subsidiary Pedanios GmbH Both Receive EU GMP Certification {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen.net|work=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2018-06-26}}</ref>\n\nIn January, 2018, Aurora became the first private company to be granted a supply agreement to the Italian market through its German subsidiary Pedanios. Aurora announced on January 23, 2018 that the first tender would consist of three lots of different cannabinoid profiles totalling 100&nbsp;kg.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/aurora-medical-cannabis-italy-1.4494494|title=Alberta medical marijuana supplier expands sales to Italy {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=2018-06-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nA statement from the company in early October 2019 reported a funding capacity for over 625,000 kg of cannabis per year, with sales and operations in 25 countries.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/aurora-cannabis-provides-update-on-global-operations-and-growth-initiatives-891846040.html|title=Aurora Cannabis Provides Update on Global Operations and Growth Initiatives|work=Cision|agency=Aurora Cannabis Inc.|date=3 October 2019}}</ref> Weeks later however, the company was reported to be having cash flow problems and the value of its stock had dropped significantly.<ref name=star/><ref name=\"cosh\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/aurora-ceo-eyes-u-s-amid-looming-carnage-for-canadian-pot-industry-1.1355362|title=Aurora CEO eyes U.S. amid looming 'carnage' for Canadian pot industry|work=BNN Bloomberg|date=29 November 2019|author=David George-Cosh|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== CanniMed takeover ===\nOn November 13, 2017, Aurora Cannabis delivered an all-stock takeover bid to [[CanniMed|CanniMed Therapeutics]]'s board of directors, which became public on November 14.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/cannimed-therapeutics-aurora-cannnabis-takeover-bid-1.4403189|title=CanniMed tells shareholders to wait while it reviews Aurora offer|work=CBC News|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en}}</ref> It claimed that it had the support of 38% of shareholders.<ref name=\":2\" /> CanniMed management responded by rejecting the offer, and proposed an alternative merger with Newstrike Resources, a recreational cannabis firm, instead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/aurora-cannabis-cannimed-therapeutics-takeover-bid-1.4417757|title=Aurora takeover bid 'makes no sense,' based on inflated share price: CanniMed|work=CBC News|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en}}</ref>  CanniMed also enacted a \"[[Shareholder rights plan|poison pill]]\" to fend off the acquisition by enacting a rights plan that would allow CanniMed shareholders to vote on the Newstrike deal.  On November 20, Aurora launched a [[hostile takeover]] bid for CanniMed, conditional on shareholders rejecting the Newstrike deal.\n\nThe Ontario Securities Commission intervened in this, the first major hostile takeover bid in Canada's cannabis industry, ordering Aurora Cannabis Inc. to provide more disclosure regarding any ties to individuals \"in a special relationship\" with target CanniMed Therapeutics Inc. and blocking CanniMed from adopting the so-called \"poison pill\" defence.  The ties were deemed unfounded by the Securities Commission.  On January 17, 2018, Newstrike shareholders approved the proposed merger.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ca.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idCAKBN1F62YO-OCABS|title=Up Cannabis-parent Newstrike's shareholders approve sale to CanniMed|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=CA|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en-CA}}</ref>  On January 18, CanniMed postponed its shareholder vote on the Newstrike deal, submitting that it will hold talks with suitor Aurora Cannabis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/news/cannimed-postpones-shareholder-vote-will-hold-talks-with-suitor-aurora-cannabis|title=CanniMed postpones shareholder vote, will hold talks with suitor Aurora Cannabis|website=business.financialpost.com|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> On January 24, it was announced that Aurora Cannabis finally hammered out a deal to acquire CanniMed Therapeutics Inc. for $1.1 billion, and CanniMed dropped its plans to acquire Newstrike.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/commodities/agriculture/nobody-got-any-sleep-last-night-aurora-cannabis-lands-cannimed-for-1-1-billion-after-marathon-talks|title='Nobody got any sleep': Aurora Cannabis lands CanniMed after marathon talks|website=business.financialpost.com|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Aurora completed their acquisition of Cannimed, with both parties agreeing to the transaction on friendly terms. This agreement brought Aurora's total patient count to 42,000 registered cannabis patients in Canada.\n\n=== MedReleaf takeover ===\nIn mid-May 2018, the company announced a planned friendly takeover of MedReleaf in a $3.2 billion stock deal already approved by the directors of both companies. The deal still requires approval by shareholders and government regulators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/business/aurora-cannabis-to-buy-medreleaf-in-all-stock-deal-worth-3-2-billion-1.3928223|title=Aurora Cannabis to buy MedReleaf in all-stock deal worth $3.2 billion|first=Armina|last=Ligaya|date=14 May 2018|website=Ctybews.ca|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> After the takeover is completed, the company will be able to produce 570,000 kilograms of cannabis at its nine grow operations in Canada and two in [[Denmark]], if it uses all of the available capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/canopy-growths-position-as-top-global-cannabis-company-shaken-by-merger-of-two-rivals|title=Canopy Growth's position as top global cannabis company shaken by merger of two rivals|date=15 May 2018|website=Ottawacitizen.com|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> The value of the new company could be as high as $7 billion, making it substantially larger than [[Canopy Growth Corporation]] with its market cap of $6.45 billion.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/our-eyes-are-on-the-global-market-aurora-acquires-medreleaf-in-largest-cannabis-deal-yet|title='Our eyes are on the global market': Aurora acquires MedReleaf in largest cannabis deal yet|date=14 May 2018|website=Business.financialpost.com|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> It would have distribution agreements in a number of countries, including Germany, [[Italy]], [[Brazil]] and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2018/05/14/edmontons-aurora-cannabis-buys-medreleaf-for-32-billion-becoming-largest-cannabis-producer-in-the-world.html|title=Edmonton's Aurora Cannabis buys MedReleaf for $3.2-billion, becoming 'largest cannabis producer in the world'  |website=Thestar.com|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> MedReleaf's German Partner filed damage claims against Aurora and MedReleaf in October 2018 for breaching the exclusive supply 2 years supply agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leafly.com/news/industry/cannamedical-sues-aurora-failed-deliveries|date=8 Nov 2018|website=Leafly.com|title=Failed Deliveries Could Cost Canadian LPs \u20ac14.7 Million|accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref> Cannamedical had sponsored MedReleaf's Markham EU-GMP certification and played a decisive role in the successful completion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/medreleaf-receives-eu-gmp-certification-for-shipment-from-its-markham-facility-and-completes-first-export-to-cannamedical-pharma-in-germany-687868341.html|date=11 July 2018|website=Newswire.com|title= MedReleaf receives EU GMP certification for shipment from its Markham facility and completes first export to Cannamedical Pharma in Germany|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Growing facilities==\n[[File:AuroraSky.jpg|thumb|Aurora Cannabis green house and Headquarters at [[Edmonton International Airport]]]]\nAurora has three operational facilities in [[Canada]] (Aurora Sky, Aurora Vie, and Aurora Mountain) plus two new facilities projected to be operational by the end of 2019, including a 1,000,000 square foot facility under construction in [[Odense|Odense, Denmark]]. Construction on the Nordic 2 project in Denmark was stopped in November 2019 when the company's stock dropped to a two year low. The Aurora Sun project in Alberta was put on a temporary hold. These decisions would lead to a savings of $190 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/national-business/aurora-shares-sink-on-weak-results-and-halting-construction-of-cannabis-plants-1850091 |title=Aurora shares sink on weak results and halting construction of cannabis plants |date=15 November 2019 |publisher=Guelph Today, Canadian Press |access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=Aurora announced after markets closed on Thursday that it will immediately cease construction of its Aurora Nordic 2 facility in Denmark to save about $80 million over the next year, as well as indefinitely defer completion of construction and commissioning at its Aurora Sun facility in Alberta to conserve $110 million.}}</ref>  \n\nAurora Mountain was Aurora's first facility, completed in 2015. It is a 55,200-square-foot production facility in [[Mountain View County, Alberta|Mountain View County]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAurora Vie is a 40,000-square-foot, fully licensed, indoor production facility in [[Pointe-Claire]], [[Quebec]]. It was the second licensed producer in Quebec, and was acquired in 2017 for $7 million when it was about 80% complete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hortidaily.com/article/38853/CAN-(QC)-Aurora-receives-cultivation-license-for-Pointe-Claire-site|title=Aurora receives cultivation license for Pointe-Claire site|website=www.hortidaily.com|access-date=2018-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120124243/http://www.hortidaily.com/article/38853/CAN-(QC)-Aurora-receives-cultivation-license-for-Pointe-Claire-site|archive-date=2018-01-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Aurora Cannabis began construction of an automated 800,000-square-foot plant in [[Alberta]] that it said would be capable of producing 100,000 kilograms of cannabis annually.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plant.ca/features/166604/|title=Aurora Sky rolls a big one|website=www.plant.ca|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> The land is part of the acreage owned by the [[Edmonton International Airport]].\n\n== Testing ==\nAll products are third-party laboratory tested with results displayed on the company's website and mobile app. In March 2017, Aurora allowed public access to a simplified Certificate of Analysis (CoA) for every cannabis product available for sale on the company's online store and mobile app. The system was developed in partnership with Anandia Labs Inc., a Canadian cannabis genetics and testing laboratory.\n\n==Retail==\nAs of April 2019, Aurora had about 17 retail outlets in western Canada through its [[strategic partnership]] with Choom Holdings Inc. and [[Mergers and acquisitions|acquisition]] of Clarity Cannabis Retail Stores, with 52 more store locations in development.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Top 5 Cannabis Retail Brands in Canada |url=https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2019/04/01/1790669/0/en/The-Top-5-Cannabis-Retail-Brands-in-Canada.html |accessdate=27 November 2019 |work=Mugglehead Media Corp |publisher=Global News |date=1 April 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Aurora opened an 11,000 [[square foot]] (1,022 square meters) [[flagship]] retail store in [[West Edmonton Mall]], making the store the largest cannabis retail space in Canada.<ref name=\"gn\">{{cite news |author1=Phil Heidenreich |title=Aurora Cannabis opening 11,000-square-foot store at West Edmonton Mall |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6221550/aurora-cannabis-stores-west-edmonton-mall/ |work=Global News |accessdate=27 November 2019 |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://auroramj.com/ Aurora Cannabis Website]\n\n{{Edmonton Businesses}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aurora Cannabis}}\n[[Category:Medicinal use of cannabis organizations]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Cannabis companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Cannabis in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian companies established in 2006]]\n", "name_user": "216.239.65.34", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aurora_Cannabis"}
{"title_page": "29th/46th Battalion (Australia)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=29th/46th Battalion\n| image= Australian 29th-46th Inf Bn at Guisika in November 1943 (AWM image 016298).jpg\n| image_size = 250\n|caption= Soldiers from the 29th/46th Battalion evacuate a wounded comrade following fighting around Gusika on New Guinea, November 1943\n|dates=1942\u201346\n|country= {{flag|Australia|23px}}\n|allegiance=\n|branch=[[Australian Army]]\n|type=[[Infantry]]\n|role=\n|size=~800\u2013900 men{{#tag:ref|At the start of the war, the normal size of an Australian infantry battalion was 910 men all ranks, however, following the reorganisation of the 5th Division along the [[Jungle division|jungle establishment]], the size dropped to 803 men all ranks.<ref>{{harvnb|Palazzo|2003|p=6}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n|command_structure=[[4th Brigade (Australia)|4th Brigade]], [[5th Division (Australia)|5th Division]]\n|garrison=\n|garrison_label=\n|nickname= East Melbourne Regiment/Brighton Rifles\n|motto=\n|colors=Black alongside Yellow\n|colors_label=Colours\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=[[Second World War]]\n* [[Huon Peninsula campaign]]\n* [[New Britain campaign]]\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|disbanded=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|commander1=\n|commander1_label=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3=\n|commander3_label=\n|notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=[[File:29th Battalion AIF Unit Colour Patch.PNG|50px]]\n|identification_symbol_label=[[Unit Colour Patch]]\n}}\n\nThe '''29th/46th Battalion''' was an [[infantry]] [[battalion]] of the [[Australian Army]]. It was formed in August 1942 by the amalgamation of two previously existing [[Australian Army Reserve|Militia]] battalions, the [[29th Battalion (Australia)|29th]] and [[46th Battalion (Australia)|46th]], which were merged following a decision by the Australian government to release manpower from the military back into industry to meet the nation's increased production requirements. Initially the 29th/46th, serving as part of the [[4th Brigade (Australia)|4th Brigade]], undertook garrison duties in Australia, however, in 1943 the battalion was deployed to [[New Guinea]] where it garrisoned [[Milne Bay]] before subsequently taking part in the [[Huon Peninsula campaign]] in support of the [[9th Division (Australia)|9th Division]]. In late 1944, after being deployed for over a year and a half, the battalion returned to Australia for a brief period of leave and reorganisation. In early 1945, however, they were again deployed overseas, this time to the island of [[New Britain]] where they undertook a [[New Britain campaign|campaign]] to contain the large [[Japan]]ese garrison. Following the end of the war the battalion was disbanded in June 1946.\n\n==History==\n===Formation===\nIn mid-1942, as a result of serious manpower shortages in the Australian economy that occurred because of an over [[Military history of Australia during World War II|mobilisation of its military forces]], the Australian government decided to return a significant number of service personnel to civilian industry by reducing the size of the Army. In order to achieve this,  a number of [[Australian Army Reserve|Militia]] [[infantry]] [[battalion]]s were disbanded while others were amalgamated.<ref>{{harvnb|Grey|2008|p=184}}</ref> The 29th/46th Battalion was one of the battalions that was formed at this time, being raised in August 1942 through the merger of two previously existing units: the [[29th Battalion (Australia)|29th Battalion (East Melbourne Regiment)]] and the [[46th Battalion (Australia)|46th Battalion (Brighton Rifles)]].<ref name=AWM>{{cite web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/units/unit_11313.asp|title=29th/46th Battalion|work=Second World War, 1939\u20131945 units |publisher=Australian War Memorial|accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref> Upon formation the battalion adopted the territorial title of the \"East Melbourne Regiment/Brighton Rifles\" in order to perpetuate the identity of its predecessor units. Assigned to the [[4th Brigade (Australia)|4th Brigade]] along with the [[22nd Battalion (Australia)|22nd]] and [[37th Battalion (Australia)|37th Battalions]], the battalion initially undertook garrison duties and training in [[Queensland]], being stationed at [[Warwick, Queensland|Warwick]], [[Brisbane]], [[Caloundra]] and [[Maroochydore]] in this time.<ref name=AWM/>\n\n===New Guinea===\nIn February 1943, with the passing of the ''Defence (Citizens Military Forces) Act 1943'', the role of the Militia was clarified with the Act expanding the geographical area in which such units could be deployed to include all of [[New Guinea]] and parts of the [[Netherlands East Indies]], [[Borneo]] and the [[Solomon Islands]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|pp=15\u201316}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|At the same time, Militia units that had 75 per cent of their actual strength, or 65 per cent of their wartime strength, volunteer for \"overseas service\" outside the geographical area prescribed by the Act, were gazetted as Australian Imperial Force (AIF) units and were deemed able to be deployed anywhere they were required.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=16}}</ref>|group=Note}} The following month, under the command of Lieutenant Colonel Kenneth Cusworth\u2014who would serve as the battalion's commanding officer throughout its existence\u2014the battalion was sent to New Guinea, along with the rest of the 4th Brigade, to reinforce the garrison at [[Milne Bay]],<ref>{{harvnb|McCarthy|1959|p=449}}</ref> where units from the [[7th Brigade (Australia)|7th Brigade]] had turned back a [[Battle of Milne Bay|Japanese landing]] the previous year.<ref name=AWM/><ref>{{harvnb|Keogh|1965|p=199}}</ref>\n\nUpon arrival, the brigade was attached to the [[5th Division (Australia)|5th Division]], which had been converted to the [[Jungle division|jungle establishment]],<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=13}}</ref> and the battalion undertook various garrison duties as well intensive jungle training and patrols.<ref name=AWM/> In September 1943, the 4th Brigade was detached from the 5th Division and dispatched to [[Lae]], where it was tasked to take over the beachhead from troops of the [[9th Division (Australia)|9th Division]] that were taking part in the fighting in [[Huon Peninsula campaign]].<ref name=AWM/> They arrived on 11 September 1943, having been dispatched aboard 12 [[Landing Craft Tank|LCTs]] and [[Landing Craft Infantry|LCIs]],<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=357}}</ref> and slowly began to relieve the troops of the [[20th Brigade (Australia)|20th Brigade]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=361}}</ref> Following this the 29th/46th Battalion began patrolling operations inland around Sattleberg, with a company being detached from the battalion as part of 'Tilley Force' to pursue the Japanese 51st Division which was fleeing inland,<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=412}}</ref> before the entire brigade, less Tilley Force, was dispatched to [[Finschhafen]] in late October.<ref name=Dexter602>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=602}}</ref> In early November the company that had been sent inland returned to the battalion at Finschhafen, arriving there on 8 November 1943.<ref name=Dexter602/>\n\nIn early December the Australian offensive was renewed and as part of this, it was decided that the 4th Brigade would play a more direct part. The brigade was to join in the advance from the coast at Gusika to Lakona and as a result, in order to benefit from the lessons in jungle warfare that had been learned by the 9th Division so far, the three Militia battalions were reinforced with training teams of experienced [[Second Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] personnel.<ref name=Dexter667>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=667}}</ref> As a part of the advance to Lakona, the 4th Brigade was tasked with capturing Fortification Hill and the 29th/46th was chosen to lead the advance along with a [[Company (military unit)|company]] from the [[37th/52nd Battalion (Australia)|37th/52nd Battalion]].{{#tag:ref|In support of the battalion were two [[platoon]]s from the 2/2nd Machine Gun Battalion, a [[troop]] of tanks from the [[1st Royal New South Wales Lancers|1st Tank Battalion]], a [[Artillery battery|battery]] of artillery, and engineers from the 2/7th Field Company. A company from the 37th/52nd Battalion and a platoon from the [[1st New Guinea Infantry Battalion]], grouped together as \"Macforce\", provided flank protection.<ref name=Dexter714/>|group=Note}} Stepping off on 5 December 1943,<ref name=Dexter714>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=714}}</ref> the advance took place in three bounds, firstly to the west towards Kamlagidu Point and to the north of the Lagoon, before turning towards Kiligia.<ref name=Dexter667/>\n\nEncountering sporadic, but nonetheless stiff opposition, the 29th/46th advanced up the coast, suffering casualties from an enemy that was expert at remaining hidden in the jungle and from mines that were laid along the various tracks that snaked through the dense scrub.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|pp=716\u2013717}}</ref> By 10 December they reached Kiligia, from which the Japanese garrison had withdrawn prior to their arrival,<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=720}}</ref> and after a brief pause as further artillery support was brought up, the advance continued on towards the Sanga River as Japanese troops from the 80th Regiment rushed to contain the Australians.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=722}}</ref> On 17 December, the 29th/46th conducted a complicated passage of lines manoeuvre, passing through the [[22nd Battalion (Australia)|22nd Battalion]], and with considerable artillery support proceeded to continue the advance up the coast crossing near the mouth of the Sanga.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=724}}</ref> By the afternoon of the following day they had reached the [[Masaweng River]], where they captured a quantity of Japanese weapons which had been abandoned on the opposite bank. After this the focus of the advance became the imposing feature of Fortification Hill and after the brigade commander moved his headquarters up to Kiligia, the 29th/46th Battalion began the advance on 19 December. Receiving sporadic Japanese mortar fire, which was met by overwhelming direct and indirect fire support from accompanying tanks and artillery, the battalion reached the summit of the hill the following day as the Japanese defenders abandoned the position.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|pp=724\u2013725}}</ref>\n\nAfter this, the 4th Brigade was assigned to the rear areas as the advance continued towards [[Madang]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=764}}</ref> In April 1944, the 29th/46th arrived there and for the next four months they provided a garrison force, before finally, in September 1944, having been deployed for almost a year and a half, the battalion received orders to return to Australia for leave and reorganisation.<ref name=AWM/>\n\n===New Britain===\nAfter reforming at [[Strathpine, Queensland]], the battalion was deployed to [[New Britain]] in January 1945 for its final campaign of the war.<ref name=AWM/> On New Britain, two brigades\u2014the [[6th Brigade (Australia)|6th]] and the [[13th Brigade (Australia)|13th]]\u2014from the Australian 5th Division had taken over from the [[40th Infantry Division (United States)|US 40th Division]] in November 1944, and after [[landing at Jacquinot Bay]], they had commenced a campaign designed to contain the Japanese forces stationed on the island. Allied intelligence had estimated these forces at around 38,000 personnel<ref>{{harvnb|Keogh|1965|p=410}}</ref> although it was later determined that this figure was closer to 93,000.<ref name=Odgers181>{{harvnb|Odgers|1988|p=181}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Long|1963|p=241}}</ref> As a result, it was decided to limit operations on New Britain to isolating the Japanese forces under General [[Hitoshi Imamura]] to their base in the Gazelle Peninsula, while wresting control of the main part of the island to the south of the line [[Battle of Wide Bay|Wide Bay]]\u2013[[Battle of Open Bay|Open Bay]].<ref>{{harvnb|Keogh|1965|p=412}}</ref>\n\nDue to a shortage of shipping, the 4th Brigade arrived behind the main force,<ref>{{harvnb|Long|1963|p=251}}</ref> with the 29th/46th arriving on the island in late January 1945.<ref name=AWM/> Following this, the 29th/46th Battalion was established to the south of the anchorage in Jacquinot Bay, around Wunung Bay.<ref name=AWM/> The Japanese resistance in the battalion's area of responsibility was limited and as a result training and long range patrols to the north and south of Jacquinot Bay occupied most of its time during this period.<ref name=AWM/> The only action encountered by the battalion was from the sections of reinforcements who were sent to Wide Bay to gain jungle warfare experience with the 13th Brigade who occupied the patrol line till the end of the war. By May 1945, the Australian advance had reached its limit of exploitation as the 5th Division reached the base of the Gazelle Peninsula and after this although patrol operations continued, only small scale clashes occurred,<ref>{{harvnb|Long|1963|p=261}}</ref> until the surrender of Japanese forces in August 1945.<ref name=Odgers181/>\n\n===Disbandment===\nFollowing the end of hostilities the battalion remained in New Britain and in September 1945 the 29th/46th Battalion led the 4th Australian Infantry Brigade ashore to occupy  [[Rabaul]] where they were used to guard Japanese prisoners of war that were awaiting repatriation back to Japan.<ref name=AWM/> Over time, however, the 29th/46th's numbers began to dwindle as men with the appropriate number of points were returned to Australia to await [[Demobilisation of the Australian military after World War II|demobilisation]] and discharge. By June 1946 this process was completed and the battalion was disbanded.<ref name=AWM/>\n\nDuring the course of the war, the 29th/46th Battalion had 38 men killed in action or died on active service, while a further 63 were wounded. Members of the battalion received the following decorations: one [[Military Cross]], three [[Military Medal]]s and six [[Mentioned in Despatches|Mentions in Despatches]].<ref name=AWM/>\n\n==Battle honours==\nThe 29th/46th received the following [[battle honour]]s for its service during the war:\n* [[South-West Pacific Area|South-West Pacific 1942\u20131945]], [[New Guinea campaign|Liberation of Australian New Guinea]]; [[Huon Peninsula campaign|Gusika\u2013Fortification Point]].<ref name=AWM/>\n\n==Notes==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dexter|first=David|title=The New Guinea Offensives| series=Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945, Series 1\u2014Army. Volume VII|year=1961|edition=1st|publisher=Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1070205/|oclc=2028994| ref=CITEREFDexter1961}}\n* {{cite book | last=Grey | first=Jeffrey | authorlink= | year=2008 | title=A Military History of Australia | edition=3rd | publisher=Cambridge University Press | location=Melbourne, Victoria | isbn=978-0-521-69791-0| ref=CITEREFGrey2008}}\n*{{cite book|last=Keogh|first=Eustace|title=South West Pacific 1941\u201345|year=1965|publisher=Grayflower Publications|location=Melbourne, Victoria|oclc=7185705|ref=CITEREFKeogh1965}}\n* {{cite book|last=Long|first=Gavin|title=The Final Campaigns|series=Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945, Series 1\u2014Army. Volume VII|year=1963|edition=1st|publisher=Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1070206/|oclc=1297619|ref=CITEREFLong1963}}\n*{{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Dudley|title=South\u2013West Pacific Area\u2014First Year: Kokoda to Wau|series=Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945 Official History Series. Series 1\u2014Army. Volume V|year=1959|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1070204/|publisher=Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|oclc=3134247| ref=CITEREFMcCarthy1959}}\n* {{cite book|last=Odgers|first=George|title=Army Australia: An Illustrated History|year=1988|publisher=Child & Associates|location=Frenchs Forest, New South Wales|isbn=0-86777-061-9| ref=CITEREFOdgers1988}}\n*{{cite book|last=Palazzo|first=Albert|chapter=Organising for Jungle Warfare|title=The Foundations of Victory: The Pacific War 1943\u20131944|year=2003|editor=Dennis, Peter |editor2=Grey, Jeffrey|publisher=Army History Unit|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/Army/ahu/docs/The_Foundations_of_Victory_Palazzo.pdf|isbn=978-0-646-43590-9| ref=CITEREFPalazzo2003}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ball |first=Peter |year=n.d. |title=Long March to Victory: Fighting with the 29th/46th Australian Infantry Battalion. New Britain 1944 to 1946|publisher=Currently unpublished}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:29th 46th Battalion (Australia)}}\n[[Category:Australian World War II battalions]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1942]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1946]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=29th/46th Battalion\n| image= Australian 29th-46th Inf Bn at Guisika in November 1943 (AWM image 016298).jpg\n| image_size = 250\n|caption= Soldiers from the 29th/46th Battalion evacuate a wounded comrade following fighting around Gusika on New Guinea, November 1943\n|dates=1942\u201346\n|country= {{flag|Australia|23px}}\n|allegiance=\n|branch=[[Australian Army]]\n|type=[[Infantry]]\n|role=\n|size=~800\u2013900 men{{#tag:ref|At the start of the war, the normal size of an Australian infantry battalion was 910 men all ranks, however, following the reorganisation of the 5th Division along the [[Jungle division|jungle establishment]], the size dropped to 803 men all ranks.<ref>{{harvnb|Palazzo|2003|p=6}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n|command_structure=[[4th Brigade (Australia)|4th Brigade]], [[5th Division (Australia)|5th Division]]\n|garrison=\n|garrison_label=\n|nickname= East Melbourne Regiment/Brighton Rifles\n|motto=\n|colors=Black alongside Yellow\n|colors_label=Colours\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=[[Second World War]]\n* [[Huon Peninsula campaign]]\n* [[New Britain campaign]]\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|disbanded=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|commander1=\n|commander1_label=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3=\n|commander3_label=\n|notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=[[File:29th Battalion AIF Unit Colour Patch.PNG|50px]]\n|identification_symbol_label=[[Unit Colour Patch]]\n}}\n\nThe '''29th/46th Battalion''' was an [[infantry]] [[battalion]] of the [[Australian Army]]. It was formed in August 1942 by the amalgamation of two previously existing [[Australian Army Reserve|Militia]] battalions, the [[29th Battalion (Australia)|29th]] and [[46th Battalion (Australia)|46th]], which were merged following a decision by the Australian government to release manpower from the military back into industry to meet the nation's increased production requirements. Initially the 29th/46th, serving as part of the [[4th Brigade (Australia)|4th Brigade]], undertook garrison duties in Australia, however, in 1943 the battalion was deployed to [[New Guinea]] where it garrisoned [[Milne Bay]] before subsequently taking part in the [[Huon Peninsula campaign]] in support of the [[9th Division (Australia)|9th Division]]. In late 1944, after being deployed for over a year and a half, the battalion returned to Australia for a brief period of leave and reorganisation. In early 1945, however, they were again deployed overseas, this time to the island of [[New Britain]] where they undertook a [[New Britain campaign|campaign]] to contain the large [[Japan]]ese garrison. Following the end of the war the battalion was disbanded in June 1946.\n\n==History==\n===Formation===\nIn mid-1942, as a result of serious manpower shortages in the Australian economy that occurred because of an over [[Military history of Australia during World War II|mobilisation of its military forces]], the Australian government decided to return a significant number of service personnel to civilian industry by reducing the size of the Army. In order to achieve this,  a number of [[Australian Army Reserve|Militia]] [[infantry]] [[battalion]]s were disbanded while others were amalgamated.<ref>{{harvnb|Grey|2008|p=184}}</ref> The 29th/46th Battalion was one of the battalions that was formed at this time, being raised in August 1942 through the merger of two previously existing units: the [[29th Battalion (Australia)|29th Battalion (East Melbourne Regiment)]] and the [[46th Battalion (Australia)|46th Battalion (Brighton Rifles)]].<ref name=AWM>{{cite web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/units/unit_11313.asp|title=29th/46th Battalion|work=Second World War, 1939\u20131945 units |publisher=Australian War Memorial|accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref> Upon formation the battalion adopted the territorial title of the \"East Melbourne Regiment/Brighton Rifles\" in order to perpetuate the identity of its predecessor units. Assigned to the [[4th Brigade (Australia)|4th Brigade]] along with the [[22nd Battalion (Australia)|22nd]] and [[37th Battalion (Australia)|37th Battalions]], the battalion initially undertook garrison duties and training in [[Queensland]], being stationed at [[Warwick]], [[Brisbane]], [[Caloundra]] and [[Maroochydore]] in this time.<ref name=AWM/>\n\n===New Guinea===\nIn February 1943, with the passing of the ''Defence (Citizens Military Forces) Act 1943'', the role of the Militia was clarified with the Act expanding the geographical area in which such units could be deployed to include all of [[New Guinea]] and parts of the [[Netherlands East Indies]], [[Borneo]] and the [[Solomon Islands]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|pp=15\u201316}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|At the same time, Militia units that had 75 per cent of their actual strength, or 65 per cent of their wartime strength, volunteer for \"overseas service\" outside the geographical area prescribed by the Act, were gazetted as Australian Imperial Force (AIF) units and were deemed able to be deployed anywhere they were required.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=16}}</ref>|group=Note}} The following month, under the command of Lieutenant Colonel Kenneth Cusworth\u2014who would serve as the battalion's commanding officer throughout its existence\u2014the battalion was sent to New Guinea, along with the rest of the 4th Brigade, to reinforce the garrison at [[Milne Bay]],<ref>{{harvnb|McCarthy|1959|p=449}}</ref> where units from the [[7th Brigade (Australia)|7th Brigade]] had turned back a [[Battle of Milne Bay|Japanese landing]] the previous year.<ref name=AWM/><ref>{{harvnb|Keogh|1965|p=199}}</ref>\n\nUpon arrival, the brigade was attached to the [[5th Division (Australia)|5th Division]], which had been converted to the [[Jungle division|jungle establishment]],<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=13}}</ref> and the battalion undertook various garrison duties as well intensive jungle training and patrols.<ref name=AWM/> In September 1943, the 4th Brigade was detached from the 5th Division and dispatched to [[Lae]], where it was tasked to take over the beachhead from troops of the [[9th Division (Australia)|9th Division]] that were taking part in the fighting in [[Huon Peninsula campaign]].<ref name=AWM/> They arrived on 11 September 1943, having been dispatched aboard 12 [[Landing Craft Tank|LCTs]] and [[Landing Craft Infantry|LCIs]],<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=357}}</ref> and slowly began to relieve the troops of the [[20th Brigade (Australia)|20th Brigade]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=361}}</ref> Following this the 29th/46th Battalion began patrolling operations inland around Sattleberg, with a company being detached from the battalion as part of 'Tilley Force' to pursue the Japanese 51st Division which was fleeing inland,<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=412}}</ref> before the entire brigade, less Tilley Force, was dispatched to [[Finschhafen]] in late October.<ref name=Dexter602>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=602}}</ref> In early November the company that had been sent inland returned to the battalion at Finschhafen, arriving there on 8 November 1943.<ref name=Dexter602/>\n\nIn early December the Australian offensive was renewed and as part of this, it was decided that the 4th Brigade would play a more direct part. The brigade was to join in the advance from the coast at Gusika to Lakona and as a result, in order to benefit from the lessons in jungle warfare that had been learned by the 9th Division so far, the three Militia battalions were reinforced with training teams of experienced [[Second Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] personnel.<ref name=Dexter667>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=667}}</ref> As a part of the advance to Lakona, the 4th Brigade was tasked with capturing Fortification Hill and the 29th/46th was chosen to lead the advance along with a [[Company (military unit)|company]] from the [[37th/52nd Battalion (Australia)|37th/52nd Battalion]].{{#tag:ref|In support of the battalion were two [[platoon]]s from the 2/2nd Machine Gun Battalion, a [[troop]] of tanks from the [[1st Royal New South Wales Lancers|1st Tank Battalion]], a [[Artillery battery|battery]] of artillery, and engineers from the 2/7th Field Company. A company from the 37th/52nd Battalion and a platoon from the [[1st New Guinea Infantry Battalion]], grouped together as \"Macforce\", provided flank protection.<ref name=Dexter714/>|group=Note}} Stepping off on 5 December 1943,<ref name=Dexter714>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=714}}</ref> the advance took place in three bounds, firstly to the west towards Kamlagidu Point and to the north of the Lagoon, before turning towards Kiligia.<ref name=Dexter667/>\n\nEncountering sporadic, but nonetheless stiff opposition, the 29th/46th advanced up the coast, suffering casualties from an enemy that was expert at remaining hidden in the jungle and from mines that were laid along the various tracks that snaked through the dense scrub.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|pp=716\u2013717}}</ref> By 10 December they reached Kiligia, from which the Japanese garrison had withdrawn prior to their arrival,<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=720}}</ref> and after a brief pause as further artillery support was brought up, the advance continued on towards the Sanga River as Japanese troops from the 80th Regiment rushed to contain the Australians.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=722}}</ref> On 17 December, the 29th/46th conducted a complicated passage of lines manoeuvre, passing through the [[22nd Battalion (Australia)|22nd Battalion]], and with considerable artillery support proceeded to continue the advance up the coast crossing near the mouth of the Sanga.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=724}}</ref> By the afternoon of the following day they had reached the [[Masaweng River]], where they captured a quantity of Japanese weapons which had been abandoned on the opposite bank. After this the focus of the advance became the imposing feature of Fortification Hill and after the brigade commander moved his headquarters up to Kiligia, the 29th/46th Battalion began the advance on 19 December. Receiving sporadic Japanese mortar fire, which was met by overwhelming direct and indirect fire support from accompanying tanks and artillery, the battalion reached the summit of the hill the following day as the Japanese defenders abandoned the position.<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|pp=724\u2013725}}</ref>\n\nAfter this, the 4th Brigade was assigned to the rear areas as the advance continued towards [[Madang]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dexter|1961|p=764}}</ref> In April 1944, the 29th/46th arrived there and for the next four months they provided a garrison force, before finally, in September 1944, having been deployed for almost a year and a half, the battalion received orders to return to Australia for leave and reorganisation.<ref name=AWM/>\n\n===New Britain===\nAfter reforming at [[Strathpine, Queensland]], the battalion was deployed to [[New Britain]] in January 1945 for its final campaign of the war.<ref name=AWM/> On New Britain, two brigades\u2014the [[6th Brigade (Australia)|6th]] and the [[13th Brigade (Australia)|13th]]\u2014from the Australian 5th Division had taken over from the [[40th Infantry Division (United States)|US 40th Division]] in November 1944, and after [[landing at Jacquinot Bay]], they had commenced a campaign designed to contain the Japanese forces stationed on the island. Allied intelligence had estimated these forces at around 38,000 personnel<ref>{{harvnb|Keogh|1965|p=410}}</ref> although it was later determined that this figure was closer to 93,000.<ref name=Odgers181>{{harvnb|Odgers|1988|p=181}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Long|1963|p=241}}</ref> As a result, it was decided to limit operations on New Britain to isolating the Japanese forces under General [[Hitoshi Imamura]] to their base in the Gazelle Peninsula, while wresting control of the main part of the island to the south of the line [[Battle of Wide Bay|Wide Bay]]\u2013[[Battle of Open Bay|Open Bay]].<ref>{{harvnb|Keogh|1965|p=412}}</ref>\n\nDue to a shortage of shipping, the 4th Brigade arrived behind the main force,<ref>{{harvnb|Long|1963|p=251}}</ref> with the 29th/46th arriving on the island in late January 1945.<ref name=AWM/> Following this, the 29th/46th Battalion was established to the south of the anchorage in Jacquinot Bay, around Wunung Bay.<ref name=AWM/> The Japanese resistance in the battalion's area of responsibility was limited and as a result training and long range patrols to the north and south of Jacquinot Bay occupied most of its time during this period.<ref name=AWM/> The only action encountered by the battalion was from the sections of reinforcements who were sent to Wide Bay to gain jungle warfare experience with the 13th Brigade who occupied the patrol line till the end of the war. By May 1945, the Australian advance had reached its limit of exploitation as the 5th Division reached the base of the Gazelle Peninsula and after this although patrol operations continued, only small scale clashes occurred,<ref>{{harvnb|Long|1963|p=261}}</ref> until the surrender of Japanese forces in August 1945.<ref name=Odgers181/>\n\n===Disbandment===\nFollowing the end of hostilities the battalion remained in New Britain and in September 1945 the 29th/46th Battalion led the 4th Australian Infantry Brigade ashore to occupy  [[Rabaul]] where they were used to guard Japanese prisoners of war that were awaiting repatriation back to Japan.<ref name=AWM/> Over time, however, the 29th/46th\u2019s numbers began to dwindle as men with the appropriate number of points were returned to Australia to await [[Demobilisation of the Australian military after World War II|demobilisation]] and discharge. By June 1946 this process was completed and the battalion was disbanded.<ref name=AWM/>\n\nDuring the course of the war, the 29th/46th Battalion had 38 men killed in action or died on active service, while a further 63 were wounded. Members of the battalion received the following decorations: one [[Military Cross]], three [[Military Medal]]s and six [[Mentioned in Despatches|Mentions in Despatches]].<ref name=AWM/>\n\n==Battle honours==\nThe 29th/46th received the following [[battle honour]]s for its service during the war:\n* [[South-West Pacific Area|South-West Pacific 1942\u20131945]], [[New Guinea campaign|Liberation of Australian New Guinea]]; [[Huon Peninsula campaign|Gusika\u2013Fortification Point]].<ref name=AWM/>\n\n==Notes==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dexter|first=David|title=The New Guinea Offensives| series=Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945, Series 1\u2014Army. Volume VII|year=1961|edition=1st|publisher=Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1070205/|oclc=2028994| ref=CITEREFDexter1961}}\n* {{cite book | last=Grey | first=Jeffrey | authorlink= | year=2008 | title=A Military History of Australia | edition=3rd | publisher=Cambridge University Press | location=Melbourne, Victoria | isbn=978-0-521-69791-0| ref=CITEREFGrey2008}}\n*{{cite book|last=Keogh|first=Eustace|title=South West Pacific 1941\u201345|year=1965|publisher=Grayflower Publications|location=Melbourne, Victoria|oclc=7185705|ref=CITEREFKeogh1965}}\n* {{cite book|last=Long|first=Gavin|title=The Final Campaigns|series=Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945, Series 1\u2014Army. Volume VII|year=1963|edition=1st|publisher=Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1070206/|oclc=1297619|ref=CITEREFLong1963}}\n*{{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Dudley|title=South\u2013West Pacific Area\u2014First Year: Kokoda to Wau|series=Australia in the War of 1939\u20131945 Official History Series. Series 1\u2014Army. Volume V|year=1959|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1070204/|publisher=Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|oclc=3134247| ref=CITEREFMcCarthy1959}}\n* {{cite book|last=Odgers|first=George|title=Army Australia: An Illustrated History|year=1988|publisher=Child & Associates|location=Frenchs Forest, New South Wales|isbn=0-86777-061-9| ref=CITEREFOdgers1988}}\n*{{cite book|last=Palazzo|first=Albert|chapter=Organising for Jungle Warfare|title=The Foundations of Victory: The Pacific War 1943\u20131944|year=2003|editor=Dennis, Peter |editor2=Grey, Jeffrey|publisher=Army History Unit|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/Army/ahu/docs/The_Foundations_of_Victory_Palazzo.pdf|isbn=978-0-646-43590-9| ref=CITEREFPalazzo2003}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ball |first=Peter |year=n.d. |title=Long March to Victory: Fighting with the 29th/46th Australian Infantry Battalion. New Britain 1944 to 1946|publisher=Currently unpublished}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:29th 46th Battalion (Australia)}}\n[[Category:Australian World War II battalions]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1942]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1946]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix placename links, replaced:Warwick\u2192Warwick,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/29th/46th_Battalion_(Australia)"}
{"title_page": "Easy Listening 4 Armageddon", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name = Easy Listening 4 Armageddon\n| type = studio\n| artist = [[Mike Ladd]]\n| cover = \n| alt = \n| released = {{Start date|1997|06|10}}\n| recorded = \n| venue = \n| studio = \n| genre = [[hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length = {{Duration|m=51|s=03}}\n| label = [[Scratchie Records]]\n| producer = {{hlist|[[Mike Ladd]]|Dennis Kelley}}\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year = \n| next_title = [[Welcome to the Afterfuture]]\n| next_year = 2000\n}}\n'''''Easy Listening 4 Armageddon''''' is the debut studio album by American hip hop musician [[Mike Ladd]]. It was released on [[Scratchie Records]] in 1997.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/easy-listening-4-armageddon-mw0000021995|title=Mike Ladd - Easy Listening 4 Armageddon|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|first=Den|last=LeRoy|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=chicagotribune>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-10-31/entertainment/9710310422_1_armageddon-dunn-spooky|title=Mike Ladd Easy Listening for Armageddon|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|first=Greg|last=Kot|date=October 31, 1997|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[JazzTimes]]''\n| rev3score = favorable<ref name=jazztimes>{{cite web|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/8433-easy-listening-for-armageddon-mike-ladd|title=Mike Ladd - Easy Listening for Armageddon|work=[[JazzTimes]]|first=Tony|last=Green|date=February 1998|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nDan LeRoy of [[AllMusic]] gave the album 4 out of 5 stars, commented that \"through a series of lo-fi beats and loops that make stunning use of a few choice samples, Ladd creates an eerie soundscape that perfectly matches his muttered musings.\"<ref name=allmusic/> Tony Green of ''[[JazzTimes]]'' wrote, \"Ignoring the all too common impulse to pile texture on top of texture, Ladd constructs 12 tracks that cajole as effectively as his richly imagistic poetry.\"<ref name=jazztimes/>\n\nGreg Kot of ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' called it \"one of the most accomplished hip-hop debuts in recent years.\"<ref name=chicagotribune/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Libations\n| length1 = 0:28\n| title2 = The Tragic Mulatto Is Neither\n| length2 = 4:18\n| title3 = Kissin' Kecia\n| length3 = 4:11\n| title4 = Bush League Junkie\n| length4 = 3:23\n| title5 = Padded Walls\n| length5 = 4:58\n| title6 = Back Stroke\n| length6 = 3:06\n| title7 = Blade Runner\n| length7 = 7:17\n| title8 = Maniac\n| length8 = 2:47\n| title9 = I'm Building a Bodacious Bodega for the Race War\n| length9 = 5:08\n| title10 = Off the Coast of Okrakoke\n| length10 = 5:28\n| title11 = Easy Listening for Armageddon\n| length11 = 4:48\n| title12 = The Post Apocalypse Arkestra\n| length12 = 5:11\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from liner notes.\n\n* [[Mike Ladd]] \u2013 vocals, production, arrangement, programming, synthesizer (8), mixing (9), art direction, front photography\n* Bruce Grant \u2013 tape loop\n* Vassos \u2013 recording (1-7, 9-12), engineering (1-7, 9-12), mixing (10)\n* Dawn Norfleet \u2013 flute (2)\n* Dennis Kelley \u2013 synthesizer (3, 8, 10), co-production (2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 11), mixing (1-8, 11, 12)\n* Jeff Cordero \u2013 guitar (3), recording (1-7, 9-12), engineering (1-7, 9-12), mixing (1-8, 11, 12)\n* Bill Green \u2013 bass guitar (8, 10)\n* John Hancock \u2013 recording (8)\n* Mio \u2013 piano (10)\n* Mums the Schemer \u2013 vocals (12)\n* Shariff Simmons \u2013 vocals (12)\n* GRFX \u2013 vocals (12)\n* Natasha Latasha Diggs \u2013 vocals (12)\n* High Priest \u2013 vocals (12)\n* Beans \u2013 vocals (12)\n* Jessica Care Moore \u2013 vocals (12)\n* Chris Athens \u2013 mastering\n* J. Stewart \u2013 art direction, design\n* Dems \u2013 bomb logo\n* Bill Harris \u2013 front photography\n* Maceo Bishop \u2013